-
You know those days where you wake up and you‚Äôre just STOKED to lift? Yeah, that‚Äôs been me on leg days. I am all about them.
-
Here‚Äôs today‚Äôs lift:
- Barbell Squats: I didn‚Äôt film my working set...I filmed my PR. 3x3 @ 105. DUDES. Squats are definitely my weak point. I only got 25# plates on the bar two weeks ago. Getting triple digits is a HUGE deal for me. I‚Äôm definitely not ready for 105# working sets (as you can see on my last rep üò¨), but it‚Äôs cool to know that number is in my (hopefully) near future!
- Dumbbell Sumo Squats: PR on my last set at 60# (what you‚Äôre seeing in the clip). I was impressed with my depth. My hip pulled through very well. 
- Dumbbell RDLS: Another PR. I could only get 6 before my grip gave out. üôÑ Other than that, 45s felt really good.
- Machine Leg Extensions: PR @ 80# for my working set! And these were superset with
- Single Leg Extensions: This is probably the most brutal superset I have in my split right now.üî•Those last couple reps involve some grunts and mumbled curses, ngl.
- Smith Machine Reverse Lunges: PR @ 75# for 3 sets of 12. These are another movement I‚Äôm proud of. Doing these on the SM allow me to go heavier because my balance is better. But even doing them with EZ bars, I notice a difference.
- Machine Lying Leg Curls: I took these down a notch last week. I COULD pull 70#, but my hips end up rising. 60# is as much as I can do without compromising form, so I‚Äôm in the process of perfecting that weight before moving back up. Oh. And these are a triple dropset. Yeah. Yeeeeeahh.üî•üôÉüî•üôÉ";}i:225;a:1:{s:14:"comments_count";i:11;}i:226;a:1:{s:11:"likes_count";i:11;}i:227;a:1:{s:4:"link";s:39:"https://www.instagram.com/p/CEu8BiZg-yY";}i:228;a:1:{s:5:"image";s:250:"https://scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/118826492_3265424123522582_4138506013967107749_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=102&_nc_ohc=7urogystPu8AX8upBLH&oh=1c2109cd5fb194cffad3323cba33fb1e&oe=5F7D5EE1";}i:229;a:1:{s:4:"type";s:7:"sidecar";}i:230;a:1:{s:8:"owner_id";i:5522187063;}i:231;a:1:{s:14:"owner_username";s:0:"";}i:232;a:1:{s:14:"owner_fullname";s:0:"";}i:233;a:1:{s:9:"owner_pic";s:0:"";}i:234;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391109777310916424";}i:235;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEu7ax_lJ9I";}i:236;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599262519;}i:237;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:561:"A Wellful Welcome this Friday afternoon! The Wellful Welcomes Katrina @knicolewriting this week! You can read the interview now on thewellful.com¬†¬†Katrina is a mental health therapist and is an awesome resource for sharing practical tools to help manage your mental health. Katrina continues to remind us how important self advocacy is as well as self expression through writing.¬†¬†Swipe to see some of our favorite quotes from her interview and learn more @knicolewriting and definitely check out her self-journal prompt¬†ebook! Happy Friday ‚ú® #thewellful";}i:238;a:1:{s:14:"comments_count";i:1;}i:239;a:1:{s:11:"likes_count";i:30;}i:240;a:1:{s:4:"link";s:39:"https://www.instagram.com/p/CEu7ax_lJ9I";}i:241;a:1:{s:5:"image";s:249:"https://scontent-sin6-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/118801382_672897906905905_1482654096224430560_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-sin6-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=101&_nc_ohc=D7YJmgnfL8oAX_tUTsQ&oh=c6e5a718ce12908820171d415a8c905f&oe=5F7E44DD";}i:242;a:1:{s:4:"type";s:7:"sidecar";}i:243;a:1:{s:8:"owner_id";i:2371698590;}i:244;a:1:{s:14:"owner_username";s:0:"";}i:245;a:1:{s:14:"owner_fullname";s:0:"";}i:246;a:1:{s:9:"owner_pic";s:0:"";}i:247;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391108975477592279";}i:248;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEu7PHOlxDX";}i:249;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599262423;}i:250;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:1338:"It seems we have replaced the social ‚Äúbadge of honor‚Äù that is physical fatigue with the belief that mental exhaustion equates to productivity.
.
Do you remember when being tired and physically fatigued was used to compare ourselves to one another? Okay, so maybe it still is... üëÄ 
.
But I think as I‚Äôve recognized the toxic culture of sleep deprivation and not listening to my body‚Äôs needs for rest, a new alternative has taken its place: the idea that mental exhaustion equates to productivity.
.
Do you ever feel like worrying is productive because at least your doing *something*? I feel that way sometimes. But when we replace the idea that we should compare physical fatigue with mental exhaustion, we still wear ourselves out and are not choosing to rest our minds.
.
We need to learn what rest looks like not only in our bodies, but for our minds, too. It‚Äôs okay to be physically AND mentally unproductive and practice body, mind, and soul rest üíï
.

